  "prompt": "How much sugar is good for health?",
  "response": "The amount of sugar considered acceptable for health can vary based on dietary guidelines and individual health needs. Here are some general recommendations:\n\n1. **World Health Organization (WHO)**: It suggests that free sugars should make up less than 10% of total daily energy intake. A further reduction to below 5% (about 25 grams or 6 teaspoons) would provide additional health benefits.\n\n2. **American Heart Association (AHA)**: The AHA recommends that added sugars should account for no more than 6% of daily caloric intake. This translates to about 25 grams (6 teaspoons) for women and about 36 grams (9 teaspoons) for men.\n\n3. **Dietary Guidelines for Americans**: These guidelines recommend limiting added sugars to less than 10% of total daily calories. \n\n**Types of Sugars**:\n- **Natural Sugars**: Found in fruits, vegetables, and dairy, these are generally considered healthy when consumed as part of whole foods.\n- **Added Sugars**: These are sugars added during processing or preparation. Limiting these is important for overall health.\n\n**Considerations**:\n- Individual health conditions (like diabetes) and lifestyle factors can affect how much sugar is appropriate for any person.\n- Whole foods with natural sugar often contain fiber, vitamins, and minerals, which provide health benefits that added sugars do not.\n\nIt's always a good idea to consult with a healthcare provider or a registered dietitian for personalized dietary advice, especially if you have specific health concerns or conditions.",
